<DOC><DOCNO> AP880324-0281 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0150EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-24 0532</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0559</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government has delivered two welcomepieces of economic news: consumer prices rose just 0.2 percent inFebruary and the economy in late 1987 expanded at the liveliestpace in nearly two years.   Falling energy and food prices in February helped restrain therise in the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index after a 0.3percent increase in January, the government said Wednesday.   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said the economygrew at a brisk 4.8 percent annual pace in the final three monthsof last year. It was the second upward revision in thefourth-quarter GNP.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Corporations' after-tax profits shot up 8.4percent in 1987, the best performance in three years, as U.S.manufacturers benefited from the weaker dollar, the government says.   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that after-tax profitsrose to $137.4 billion last year, the first increase since a 12percent rise in 1984.   U.S. companies have been enjoying an export boom this past yearas declines in the dollar made American products competitive againon overseas markets.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Chrysler Corp. selling surge ran counter to aslight overall decline in mid-March domestic car sales, automakershave reported.   Analysts said Wednesday that higher-than-expected sales due toincentives and a stock-crash rebound appeared to be tapering off.   The eight companies that make autos in the United States sold189,245 cars in the eight sales days from March 11-20, down from217,939 in nine sales days in the comparable 1987 period.</TEXT><DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texaco Inc. has won final bankruptcycourt approval for a plan that would settle its multibillion-dollardispute with Pennzoil Co. and bring it out of Chapter 11 protectionearly next month.   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard Schwartzberg on Wednesdayconfirmed the reorganization plan, which features an agreement byTexaco to pay Pennzoil $3 billion to drop a $10.3 billion judgmentheld by Pennzoil against Texaco.   When the plan goes into effect on April 7, Texaco officiallywill be free from legal constraints that have limited itsoperations since its historic bankruptcy filing last April 12.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Northwest Airlines says it will ban smoking onall its domestic flights except to and from Hawaii and on someforeign routes.   The ban announced Wednesday makes Minneapolis-based Northwestthe first major U.S. airline to mandate a smoke-free travelenvironment in the air. It goes beyond federal regulations, whichwill outlaw smoking on all domestic flights of two hours or lessstarting April 23.   Northwest's stringent non-smoking policy appears to be aimed atattracting new passengers but could backfire and cost the carriersome traffic, some analysts believe.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court, in a decision threejustices called anti-union, has ruled the government may limit afamily's eligibility for food stamps when a family member is onstrike.   The court said Wednesday that a 1981 federal law imposing suchlimits does not violate any constitutional rights.   In another decision, the court ruled in an Illinois case thatshort-term notes used to finance public housing projects are notexempt from federal estate taxes.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>